Define the preprocess_image function

  • def preprocess_image(filepath, target_size=(64, 64)): this function definition takes two arguments, the filepath of the image to be preprocessed, and an optional target_size tuple specifying the desired dimensions of the resized image (default is 64x64).
    • if not filepath.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg', '.tiff', '.bmp', '.gif')): this conditional statement checks if the filepath extension is not one of the accepted image file formats. If the file is not an image, the function prints a warning message and returns None.
    • img = cv2.imread(filepath, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE): this line reads the image file from the given filepath and converts it to grayscale using the OpenCV library.
    • if img is None: this conditional statement checks if the image was read successfully. If not, the function prints an error message and returns None.
    • img = cv2.resize(img, target_size): this line resizes the image to the specified target_size using the OpenCV library.
    • img = Image.fromarray(img): this line converts the OpenCV image (NumPy array) to a PIL Image object.
    • return img: this line returns the preprocessed PIL Image object.
In [5]:
def preprocess_image(filepath, target_size=(64, 64)):
    if not filepath.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg', '.tiff', '.bmp', '.gif')):
        print(f'Skipping non-image file: {filepath}')
        return None

    img = cv2.imread(filepath, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)

    if img is None:
        print(f'Error reading file: {filepath}')
        return None

    img = cv2.resize(img, target_size)
    img = Image.fromarray(img)
    return img

Define EmotionDataset class

  • class EmotionDataset(Dataset): this class definition inherits from the Dataset class in the PyTorch library, and defines a custom dataset for the emotion recognition task
    • def init(self, filepaths, labels, transform=None): the constructor of the EmotionDataset class takes three arguments: filepaths (list of image filepaths), labels (list of corresponding emotion labels), and an optional transform (image transformations to be applied)
      • self.valid_filepaths: an empty list that will store the filepaths of successfully preprocessed images
      • self.valid_labels: an empty list that will store the corresponding labels of successfully preprocessed images
      • for filepath, label in zip(filepaths, labels): a loop that iterates over the provided filepaths and labels
        • img = preprocess_image(filepath): preprocesses the image at the given filepath by calling the preprocess_image() function
        • if img is not None: this conditional statement checks if the preprocessed image is not None, meaning the image has been successfully read and preprocessed
          • self.valid_filepaths.append(filepath): appends the filepath of the successfully preprocessed image to the 'valid_filepaths' list
          • self.valid_labels.append(label): appends the corresponding label of the successfully preprocessed image to the 'valid_labels' list
      • self.transform: stores the image transformations to be applied (if any)
    • def len(self): this method returns the length (number of images) of the dataset
      • return len(self.valid_filepaths): returns the number of valid filepaths in the dataset
    • def getitem(self, idx): this method takes an index as input and returns the preprocessed image and its corresponding label at that index
      • img = preprocess_image(self.valid_filepaths[idx]): preprocesses the image at the given index in the 'valid_filepaths' list
      • label = self.valid_labels[idx]: retrieves the corresponding label at the given index from the 'valid_labels' list
      • if self.transform: this conditional statement checks if there are any image transformations to be applied
        • img = self.transform(img): applies the specified image transformations to the preprocessed image
    • return img, label: returns the preprocessed (and transformed) image and its corresponding label
In [9]:
class EmotionDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, filepaths, labels, transform=None):
        self.valid_filepaths = []
        self.valid_labels = []
        for filepath, label in zip(filepaths, labels):
            img = preprocess_image(filepath)
            if img is not None:
                self.valid_filepaths.append(filepath)
                self.valid_labels.append(label)
        self.transform = transform

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.valid_filepaths)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        img = preprocess_image(self.valid_filepaths[idx])
        label = self.valid_labels[idx]
        if self.transform:
            img = self.transform(img)
        return img, label

Define the resnet18 model

  • def create_resnet18_model(num_classes=8): a function definition to create a ResNet-18 model with the specified number of output classes (default is 8)

    • model = models.resnet18(weights=ResNet18_Weights.IMAGENET1K_V1): initializes a pre-trained ResNet-18 model with weights from the ImageNet dataset
    • model.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, 64, kernel_size=7, stride=2, padding=3, bias=False): replaces the first convolutional layer of the ResNet-18 model with a new convolutional layer that takes a single-channel (grayscale) input image instead of the default three-channel (RGB) input
    • num_ftrs = model.fc.in_features: retrieves the number of input features for the fully connected layer in the ResNet-18 model
    • model.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, num_classes): replaces the final fully connected layer of the ResNet-18 model with a new linear layer that has the specified number of output classes
    • return model: returns the modified ResNet-18 model

  • output_size = len(emotions): sets the number of output classes equal to the number of emotions (which is 8 in this case)

  • model = create_resnet18_model(num_classes=output_size): creates a modified ResNet-18 model with the specified number of output classes using the create_resnet18_model() function

  • model.to(device): moves the model to the computation device (either GPU or CPU) specified earlier

In [13]:
def create_resnet18_model(num_classes=8):
    model = models.resnet18(weights=ResNet18_Weights.IMAGENET1K_V1)
    model.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, 64, kernel_size=7, stride=2, padding=3, bias=False)
    num_ftrs = model.fc.in_features
    model.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, num_classes)
    return model

output_size = len(emotions)

Define the calculate_accuracy function

  • def calculate_accuracy(y_pred, y_true): a function definition that calculates the accuracy of the model's predictions given the predicted values (y_pred) and the true labels (y_true)
    • y_pred = torch.argmax(y_pred, dim=1): finds the index of the highest value (predicted class) along dimension 1 (columns) of the input tensor y_pred, which corresponds to the model's predicted class for each sample in the batch
    • correct = (y_pred == y_true).sum().item(): calculates the number of correct predictions by comparing the predicted classes (y_pred) to the true labels (y_true), summing the resulting tensor, and converting it to a Python scalar using the item() method
    • return correct / len(y_true): returns the accuracy by dividing the number of correct predictions by the total number of samples in the batch (length of y_true)
In [14]:
def calculate_accuracy(y_pred, y_true):
    y_pred = torch.argmax(y_pred, dim=1)
    correct = (y_pred == y_true).sum().item()
    return correct / len(y_true)

Train and validate the model

This code snippet trains the model and evaluates it on the validation set for the specified number of epochs. It also implements early stopping to prevent overfitting.

  • Initialize lists to store training and validation losses and accuracies.

  • Define early stopping parameters:

    • early_stopping_patience: the number of consecutive epochs without improvement in validation loss before stopping the training process
    • epochs_without_improvement: a counter that keeps track of the number of epochs without improvement in validation loss
    • best_val_loss: the best validation loss achieved so far, initialized to positive infinity

  • Start a loop that runs for the specified number of epochs:

    1. Set the model to training mode using model.train().

    2. Initialize the running loss and corrects counters to zero.

    3. Loop through the batches of images and labels in the training data loader:

      • Move the inputs and labels to the computation device (GPU or CPU).
      • Zero the gradients of the optimizer using optimizer.zero_grad().
      • Pass the inputs through the model to get the outputs.
      • Compute the loss using the criterion.
      • Backpropagate the loss using loss.backward().
      • Update the model parameters using optimizer.step().
      • Update the running loss and corrects counters.

    4. Calculate the average training loss and accuracy by dividing the running values by the size of the training dataset. Append these values to the respective lists.

    5. Set the model to evaluation mode using model.eval().

    6. Initialize the running loss and corrects counters to zero.

    7. Loop through the batches of images and labels in the validation data loader (with gradients disabled using torch.no_grad()):

      • Move the inputs and labels to the computation device (GPU or CPU).
      • Pass the inputs through the model to get the outputs.
      • Compute the loss using the criterion.
      • Update the running loss and corrects counters.

    8. Calculate the average validation loss and accuracy by dividing the running values by the size of the validation dataset. Append these values to the respective lists.

    9. Update the learning rate using the scheduler's step() method.

    10. Print the training and validation losses and accuracies for the current epoch.

    11. Check for early stopping:

      • If the validation loss has improved, update the best validation loss and reset the epochs_without_improvement counter.
      • If the validation loss has not improved, increment the epochs_without_improvement counter.
      • If the epochs_without_improvement counter reaches the early_stopping_patience value, stop the training process and print a message.
In [16]:
train_losses = []
train_accuracies = []
val_losses = []
val_accuracies = []

# Early stopping parameters
early_stopping_patience = 5
epochs_without_improvement = 0
best_val_loss = float('inf')

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    # Training phase
    model.train()
    running_loss = 0.0
    running_corrects = 0
    for inputs, labels in train_loader:
        inputs = inputs.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)

        optimizer.zero_grad()

        outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        running_loss += loss.item()
        running_corrects += calculate_accuracy(outputs, labels) * inputs.size(0)

    train_loss = running_loss / len(train_dataset)
    train_accuracy = running_corrects / len(train_dataset)
    train_losses.append(train_loss)
    train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)

    # Validation phase
    model.eval()
    running_loss = 0.0
    running_corrects = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for inputs, labels in val_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            running_loss += loss.item()
            running_corrects += calculate_accuracy(outputs, labels) * inputs.size(0)

    val_loss = running_loss / len(val_dataset)
    val_accuracy = running_corrects / len(val_dataset)
    val_losses.append(val_loss)
    val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)
    scheduler.step()

    print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}] - Loss (Train): {train_loss:.4f}, Loss (Val): {val_loss:.4f}, Acc (Train): {train_accuracy:.4f}, Acc (Val): {val_accuracy:.4f}')

    # Check for early stopping
    if val_loss < best_val_loss:
        best_val_loss = val_loss
        epochs_without_improvement = 0
    else:
        epochs_without_improvement += 1

    if epochs_without_improvement >= early_stopping_patience:
        print(f"Early stopping at epoch {epoch+1}.")
        break

Evaluate the model on the test set

  1. Set the model to evaluation mode using model.eval().

  2. Initialize the test_running_loss counter and num_batches counter to zero.

  3. Loop through the batches of images and labels in the test data loader:

Plot the training and validation losses

This plot shows the training and validation losses during the training process.

  • The x-axis represents the epoch number, which indicates the progress of the training process.
  • The y-axis represents the loss value, which is the objective function that the model is trying to minimize during training.
  • The blue line (labeled 'Training loss') shows the training loss at each epoch. It represents how well the model is fitting the training dataset. As the model learns, the training loss is expected to decrease.
  • The orange line (labeled 'Validation loss') shows the validation loss at each epoch. It represents how well the model generalizes to new, unseen data. The validation loss is used to monitor the model's performance on a held-out dataset and to prevent overfitting.
  • Ideally, both training and validation losses should decrease over time, and the validation loss should closely follow the training loss. If the validation loss starts increasing while the training loss continues to decrease, it might indicate that the model is overfitting to the training dataset.

Plot confusion matrix

This code snippet generates a confusion matrix plot for the model's predictions on the test dataset.

  1. Set the model to evaluation mode using model.eval().
  2. Initialize empty lists y_pred and y_true to store the predicted and true labels, respectively.
  3. Loop through the batches of images and labels in the test data loader:
    • Move the inputs and labels to the computation device (GPU or CPU).
    • Pass the inputs through the model to get the outputs.
    • Get the predicted class by finding the index with the maximum value in the outputs (using torch.max()).
    • Extend y_pred and y_true lists with the predicted and true labels, respectively, after converting them to NumPy arrays and moving them back to the CPU.
  4. Compute the confusion matrix using the confusion_matrix() function from scikit-learn, with y_true and y_pred as inputs.
  5. Define the labels variable as the list of emotions.
  6. Create a heatmap plot using the Seaborn library:
    • Initialize a figure with a defined size (8x8 inches).
    • Use sns.heatmap() with the confusion matrix, annotations, color map ('Blues'), format for annotations ('g'), x-axis tick labels, y-axis tick labels, and axes object.
    • Set the x-axis label to 'Predicted Labels'.
    • Set the y-axis label to 'True Labels'.
  7. Display the plot using plt.show().

The resulting confusion matrix plot shows the performance of the model in terms of how it classified the test dataset. Each row represents the true labels, and each column represents the predicted labels. The diagonal elements represent the number of instances where the predicted label matches the true label. Off-diagonal elements indicate misclassifications. The confusion matrix helps identify which classes the model has difficulties classifying correctly and if there are any systematic errors in the predictions.

def visualize_predictions(model, device, loader, class_names):
    model.eval()
    dataiter = iter(loader)
    images, labels = dataiter.next()
    images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
    with torch.no_grad():
        outputs = model(images)
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs, 1)

    images = images.cpu()
    predicted = predicted.cpu()

    predicted_text = [class_names[predicted[i]] for i in range(len(predicted))]
    labels_text = [class_names[labels[i]] for i in range(len(labels))]

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 5, figsize=(10, 5))
    for i, ax in enumerate(axs.flat):
        if images[i].dim() == 2:
            ax.imshow(images[i], cmap='gray')
        else:
            ax.imshow(images[i].permute(1, 2, 0).squeeze())
        ax.set_title(f'True: {labels_text[i]}\nPredicted: {predicted_text[i]}')
        ax.axis('off')
        
    plt.show()

Model summary

The output of the summary() function will show the model's layers, their output shapes, and the number of parameters. This information is useful for understanding the model's architecture and its complexity, as well as for debugging purposes.

Explanation of the key information provided in the result:

  1. Layer (type): This column shows the type of layer used in the network, such as Conv2d (2D convolutional layer), BatchNorm2d (2D batch normalization layer), ReLU (rectified linear unit activation function), and so on.
  2. Output Shape: This column displays the shape of the output tensor after passing through each layer. The -1 in the first dimension represents the batch size, which can be any positive integer.
  3. Param #: This column shows the number of trainable parameters for each layer. The total number of trainable parameters in the network is shown at the end of the summary.

Additional information provided at the end of the summary includes:

  • Total params: The total number of parameters in the model (11,174,344 in this case).

  • Trainable params: The number of parameters that will be updated during training (11,174,344 in this case).

  • Non-trainable params: The number of parameters that will not be updated during training (0 in this case).

  • Input size (MB): The memory size of the input tensor (0.02 MB in this case).

  • Forward/backward pass size (MB): The memory size required to store intermediate values during forward and backward passes (5.13 MB in this case).

  • Params size (MB): The memory size of the model's parameters (42.63 MB in this case).

  • Estimated Total Size (MB): The estimated total memory size required by the model (47.77 MB in this case).

        filepaths.append(os.path.join(emotion_dir, filename))
        labels.append(label)

    filepaths, labels, test_size=0.15, stratify=labels, random_state=42)

def preprocess_image(filepath, target_size=(64, 64)):
    if not filepath.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg', '.tiff', '.bmp', '.gif')):
        print(f'Skipping non-image file: {filepath}')
        return None

    img = cv2.imread(filepath, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)

    if img is None:
        print(f'Error reading file: {filepath}')
        return None

    img = cv2.resize(img, target_size)
    img = img / 255.0
    return img

train_data = []
for filepath, label in zip(X_train, y_train):
    img = preprocess_image(filepath)
    if img is not None:
        train_data.append((img, label))

class MLP(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden1_size, hidden2_size, output_size):
        super(MLP, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden1_size)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(hidden1_size, hidden2_size)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(hidden2_size, output_size)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1)
        x = torch.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = torch.relu(self.fc2(x))
        x = torch.softmax(self.fc3(x), dim=1)
        return x

model = MLP(input_size, hidden1_size, hidden2_size, output_size)
model.to(device)

def calculate_accuracy(y_pred, y_true):
    y_pred = torch.argmax(y_pred, dim=1)
    correct = (y_pred == y_true).sum().item()
    return correct / len(y_true)

model = MLP(input_size, hidden1_size, hidden2_size, output_size)

        labels = labels.to(device)
        model.to(device)

        optimizer.zero_grad()

        outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        running_loss += loss.item()
        running_corrects += calculate_accuracy(outputs,
                                               labels) * inputs.size(0)

    train_loss = running_loss / len(train_dataset)
    train_accuracy = running_corrects / len(train_dataset)
    train_losses.append(train_loss)
    train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)

    model.eval()
    running_loss = 0.0
    running_corrects = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for inputs, labels in val_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            model.to(device)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            running_loss += loss.item()
            running_corrects += calculate_accuracy(
                outputs,labels) * inputs.size(0)

    val_accuracy = running_corrects / len(val_dataset)
    val_losses.append(val_loss)
    val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

    for filename in os.listdir(emotion_dir):
        filepaths.append(os.path.join(emotion_dir, filename))
        labels.append(label)

    filepaths, labels, test_size=0.15, stratify=labels, random_state=42)

    X_temp, y_temp, test_size=0.176, stratify=y_temp, random_state=42)


def preprocess_image(filepath, target_size=(64, 64)):
    if not filepath.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg', '.tiff', '.bmp', '.gif')):
        print(f'Skipping non-image file: {filepath}')
        return None

    img = cv2.imread(filepath, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)

    if img is None:
        print(f'Error reading file: {filepath}')
        return None

    img = cv2.resize(img, target_size)
    img = Image.fromarray(img)
    return img

train_data = []
for filepath, label in zip(X_train, y_train):
    img = preprocess_image(filepath)
    if img is not None:
        train_data.append((img, label))

val_data = []
for filepath, label in zip(X_val, y_val):
    img = preprocess_image(filepath)
    if img is not None:
        val_data.append((img, label))

test_data = []
for filepath, label in zip(X_test, y_test):
    img = preprocess_image(filepath)
    if img is not None:
        test_data.append((img, label))
        
class EmotionDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, filepaths, labels, transform=None):
        self.valid_filepaths = []
        self.valid_labels = []
        for filepath, label in zip(filepaths, labels):
            img = preprocess_image(filepath)
            if img is not None:
                self.valid_filepaths.append(filepath)
                self.valid_labels.append(label)
        self.transform = transform

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.valid_filepaths)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        img = preprocess_image(self.valid_filepaths[idx])
        label = self.valid_labels[idx]
        if self.transform:
            img = self.transform(img)
        return img, label

transform_train = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
    transforms.RandomRotation(20),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
])

transform_test = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.ToTensor(),
])

train_dataset = EmotionDataset(X_train, y_train, transform=transform_train)
val_dataset = EmotionDataset(X_val, y_val, transform=transform_test)
test_dataset = EmotionDataset(X_test, y_test, transform=transform_test)

val_loader = DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True, num_workers=4)
test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True, num_workers=4)

device = torch.device("cuda:0" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")

class CNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes=8):
        super(CNN, self).__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, 16, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.pool = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0)
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(128 * 4 * 4, 512)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(512, num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv1(x)))
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv2(x)))
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv3(x)))
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv4(x)))
        x = x.view(-1, 128 * 4 * 4)
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.fc2(x)
        return x

output_size = len(emotions)
model = CNN(num_classes=output_size)
model.to(device)

criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)

def calculate_accuracy(y_pred, y_true):
    y_pred = torch.argmax(y_pred, dim=1)
    correct = (y_pred == y_true).sum().item()
    return correct / len(y_true)

train_losses = []
train_accuracies = []
val_losses = []
val_accuracies = []

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    model.train()
    running_loss = 0.0
    running_corrects = 0
    for inputs, labels in train_loader:
        inputs = inputs.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)
        model.to(device)

        optimizer.zero_grad()

        outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        running_loss += loss.item()
        running_corrects += calculate_accuracy(outputs,
                                               labels) * inputs.size(0)

    train_loss = running_loss / len(train_dataset)
    train_accuracy = running_corrects / len(train_dataset)
    train_losses.append(train_loss)
    train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)

    model.eval()
    running_loss = 0.0
    running_corrects = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for inputs, labels in val_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            model.to(device)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            running_loss += loss.item()
            running_corrects += calculate_accuracy(
                outputs,labels) * inputs.size(0)

    val_loss = running_loss / len(val_dataset)
    val_accuracy = running_corrects / len(val_dataset)
    val_losses.append(val_loss)
    val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)
    scheduler.step()

    print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}] - Loss (Train): {train_loss:.4f}, Loss (Val): {val_loss:.4f}, Acc (Train): {train_accuracy:.4f}, Acc (Val): {val_accuracy:.4f}')
